AWS Cloudfront - speeding up app and secure at global scale 

Content delivery network ( CDN ) - distributes your content ( web pages , api’s , videos , data) to users around the world world that have low latency 

* Instead of users reaching back to the origin server like an s3 bucket/ ec2 instance = edge locations are used *

1. Caches content at edge locations globally 
2. When someone requests that content , they are served by the nearest location 
3. this reduces load on your origin servers and improves speed for end users 

Pros : 
- Fewer resources used by origin server  & Fast loader times 
- Improved user experience & Improves read performance 
- Integrates well with AWS shield and AWS web application firewall ( WAF) = DDoS protection - look over again 


AWS has 261 points of presence ( pips ) ( edge locations ) = so content can be accessed almost anywhere 


Cloudfront at a high level  ( content delivery )
  → client requests to view image from website -> request sent to cloudfront edge location (server) (if cached , pops up immediately) 
  → if not cloudfront reaches out to the origin ( s3 / http server ) →  content sent back to edge location + cached   →  client receives content


When using private AWS with Origin access control and bucket policies , cloudfront  is the only way to access your origin s3 files directly


 A Cloudfront origin = where cloudfront fetches content from 

*Cloudfront then pulls from that origin/source and caches at edge locations for faster delivery to users*


2 main categories include -> S3 buckets , AWS hosted infrastructure like EC2 , load balancers OR
->  HTTP server 


S3 bucket - for distributing static content and files and caching at edge 

  → Cloudfront integrates tightly with s3  , allowing direct origin access control configuration and caching 
  → OAC (origin access control) used to securely access s3 buckets replacing OAI (identity) 
  → Enhanced security is achieved with IAM policies with OAC = ensures only cloud front can access s3 bucket 


 → Cloudfront can handle direct uploads & pass them to s3 bucket
- Users upload directly through cloudfront
- Cloudfront securely forwards POST requests to s3 bucket 
- Enhances security by adding cloudfront protections 
- Performance benefits as it’s using cloudfront global edge locations 

  *Cloud front can also serve as an ingress to securely upload files to s3 by forwarding POST requests*
  *Ingress = traffic/data entering your system


HTTP server 

 → HTTP origins can be any web server—on AWS (like EC2) or external.
 → CloudFront forwards requests (GET, POST, etc.) to the origin.
 → Origin generates dynamic responses (e.g., API, HTML).
 → You can configure caching, headers, and query strings to control content delivery.
